data.content:
Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>`, which lets you inspect the exception and pinpoints exactly which line threw:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));

    Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName); // bonus: verify details
}
```

**Why:**
- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws — it can mask bugs
- `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` scopes the check to the specific call
- You get the exception back to assert on `Message`, `ParamName`, etc.

Use `Assert.Throws<T>` instead if you also want to match derived exception types.
